segments.text: the Senate was called on to act react to the design of things of a separate school and so on there was I think a little reaction to the Senate among other faculty members who would like a little more money to what was going to the Bush School by the legislature etc and not one can understand that I can sense that in the Senate meeting
Are there any reactions that you can share that you heard about from President Bush and or other members of the Bush family as this proposal process is underway?
No, I have no special hints.
He's commented occasionally.
It appeared to be a good proposal.
And, of course, the famous story about either Louis Halbooty, I guess, who sent him the precinct by precinct election returns around Rice and around Houston and around here.
I have a feeling that may have had as much to do with it as anything else.

except it was a solid concrete proposal and there was no way he could go to Austin and where the hell else in Texas if you and Houston and Rice have got no land John Lindsay I asked John Lindsay one time when did he become aware that A&M was almost certainly the winner and he chuckled and said well most clearly I thought that
when the head of the Rice proposal and the U of H proposal each came together to talk to me about... And see if we'd join.
And see if we'd join in making it a three-way deal.
He said, I thought we must be in pretty good shape at that point.
In hindsight, can you think of anything that A&M might have done even better?
They might have done better had they not put it as part of liberal arts.
Oh.
The school.
Was there anything that came about as a result of that?
Yes.
The dean of liberal arts and political science.
And the dean of liberal arts desperately wanted to hold on to it.
He has got us involved with faculty from all over the university.
As a result, the faculty structure, the course structure, the curriculum are absolute messes.
Oh, okay.
And we can't disengage easily.
But now that separation of the Bush School
As a unit reporting directly to the provost, that has now been done.
That has been done as of last fall.
And you think that's an appropriate decision?
Yes.
Is that?
No, I think getting Herman out was a political act.
I don't think the Bush family had anything to do with it.
I'm trying to find out exactly how that legislative money
was appropriated with an implication that if Herman stayed, they wouldn't get it.
I think I'm reminded of a story of President Harding.
He was visiting William Allen White on his way to the West Coast.
And he was pacing the library in White's house, and suddenly Harding blurts out,
My friends, my goddamn friends.
I can take care of my enemies, but my goddamn friends.
And I think this was friends of Bush.
And Harding never said anymore and went on to Alaska and died.
And you're implying self-appointed friends doing something.
Doing what they thought would be a favor.
Let's see.
What have we left out?
Oh, I don't know.
I had some notes from what I've previously been involved in.
Oh, one thing I've been glad to see at A&M is in the last few years they've done some indoctrination for new department heads.
And it strikes me some deans ought to have done that.
And you think that's a good...
It sure as hell is.
Now, I was out of public administration.
There was no great mystery.
I'd been involved with the school, which was in effect a small department, and all the decisions, et cetera.
But I think of sociology, my sociology head, paralleling me, went over his budget, 10,000, because he didn't really quite understand what
Though I haven't got the right term earmarking, you know, you make a commitment to spend, you don't have it.
So he went over his budget 10,000 because he didn't encumber.
What about an orientation session a day or so for all new faculty to learn more about the institution?
Well, I used to do this and go over the rules and regulations, for example, as to what you could do and not do and what you jolly well better do if you don't want to trouble with complaints, etc.
The year I had my ten new faculty, I came and said, Sam, just before you come in, I'm going to take them for a day.
And we're going down.
how you get started here.
And one could have done a couple more days.
I also had made it a practice to new faculty members get somebody to escort them to the first hill practice over in the field house.
So things of that sort.
I came here as a self-appointed critic of A&M because it was different than what my undergraduate school, little liberal arts school at Austin College and Rice.
But I gradually became persuaded that A&M is distinctive and that each institution ought to be.
What are the keys to understanding A&M?
Well, oddly enough, the core is at the base of a lot of it, because the core has caused other people to organize also.
Mm-hm.
And I got this out of both sociology and the military that
You become loyal to a large group because you have a small group of friends.
You don't get loyalty to the large group in the abstract.
Now I haven't been able to do that.
I think I sold the general who was dean of students on fraternities in part by making that kind of point to him, and I think he understood it.

because the army early in world war ii tried to abolish individual patches for individual units in a misguided notion that they were going to all think about one army and some few sociologists stouffer chicago and some others made the point look this ain't how it's done and they began to get from all over the military about inability to have their own units
which isn't divisive except in a very limited way.
And the army and military went hog wild over patches and distinctive items, names, et cetera, for units and so on.
So the fraternities and sororities, the organizations,
It's got an undergraduate organization.
I think the MSC mechanism is very basic.
People can find a place.
There are all kinds there.
And that's where it begins.
Is A&M Spirit special?
Yes.
Now, Cornell had a great deal of Spirit.
And I would say Dartmouth.
also.
But I think spirit also tends to be evidenced in proportion of people who make annual giving.
There's a study of fraternities.
The fraternity men, who are thought to be, you know, a lot of friends who think they're
intellectual anti-college give more to their institutions in proportion than any other group.
Are you aware there are now more fraternity and sorority members at A&M than there are members of the Corps?
No, I wasn't.
And there is a higher percentage, per capita percentage, undergraduate fraternity and sorority members here than at the University of Texas at Austin.
Oh, no.
I have been connected with our own chapter here.
I was the young gentleman who was viewed as the founder of the first fraternity here was the guy who slept with the student.
He and I became .
And having been a National Officer of the fraternity, I helped him get his, I forget the name of his group, organized and with bylaws and such things.
And then I helped one of the sororities.
Likewise, Vi Burke was associated with one of the sororities, and when they got their charter, I gave the main talk at the banquet, I think.
All right, I've got then two final questions.
Let's make believe that someone gives you a check for a million dollars today.
and there is only one requirement on that check, that you pass the money on to Texas A&M, but you choose the use that would be made for that gift.
If you were doing something significant for Texas A&M, for what purpose would you want that generosity used?
Oh, I don't know.
I'm inclined to think I would give it to the president and tell him to use it wherever he thinks he needs it.
That's very thoughtful.
I would like to comment on two things I failed at.
that I thought were damn good ideas and still do.
Oh, do offer that.
This is in the educational world for, well, there are two or three here.
For some time, we had special sections in 206 and 207 for foreign students.
I don't think they do anymore.
I have no evidence of that.
I thought this served a very useful purpose.
And I, for example, had Kwong Ro, I had Marina Weiss, who was, Marina Weiss was interesting.
She was, she neither looked it nor her name, but she was Puerto Rican and fluent in Spanish.
As she told me, her custom was with an American government class to

go in and function for a week in their perfect eastern English and then the second week she would start a little bit of Spanish and there would influence Spanish and there would be red faces all over the room.
A woman in teaching us Mexicans and Puerto Ricans but Marina was very good
So there, but that, you've got to have people to do it, but it was feasible.
Then I began, and this was very interesting to do, and several people willing, Warren Dixon took the lead in what we called contract courses.
A student could contract to do an A, B, or C. And this suited a lot of people.
They didn't have, they had to do just what necessary to get a C, etc.
And there was one lecture period a week for handling the things that needed to be done.
But the reading was carefully chosen.
And each week or each two weeks, there was an exam.
Now you could come back and take the second thing.
You could come back and take that exam several more times till you got it.
But you could get your C, but you had to pass it.
And now it meant a lot of initial work for the faculty.
But those were very popular, particularly engineers who were desperate to get through.
They knew exactly what they had to do.
But it was very funny.
Lebo, who was head of journalism, said, I'm not going to allow students to sign up for this.
What the hell do you think you're doing?
And a couple of my own faculty said, are you trying to do away with professors?
Because this means a lot less lecturing.
The faculty work with the A students who really can do it.
And they're spending time.
And you don't need half as many faculty.
But I finally, this, when I left.
Don't forget your lapel.
We've got one more question.
I could not get these.
And also, this, of course, also involved program learning.
which I thought was eminently sensible for heaven knows the state and local government, the constitutional part, a lot of it is working.
Could never get them to really take hold.
Last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M today?
Well, I've been delighted and enjoyed what I've done and been here.
We expect to remain here.
Dorothy's become accommodated to us.
It took a year or two.
And she'd been in high school, and I went to Harrison Hearth and she, and said she could teach composition, and A&M is expanding, you know, and has got to do composition throughout its years.
And so they pick her up as a...
a lecture, and she'd been here 20 years.
I said, if I were her, I'll sue.
But no, we've been delighted, and the place has grown, and it's a totally different place from what it was.
I think, say, much of the 2020 is feasible if they'll
unloose some of the administrative system occasionally and some money.
That's great with that.
